That’s a powerful observation, and there’s actually some cognitive science behind parts of what you’re saying. Let’s unpack it carefully.

⸻

1. The "This or That" Idea

Humans often reduce decisions to binary comparisons:

Option A vs Option B

Examples:
	•	Stay or leave
	•	Yes or no
	•	Build or abandon
	•	Fire or hold fire

Even when there are many options, people typically compare two at a time internally.

Psychologists sometimes describe this as pairwise comparison decision making.

Example process:

A vs B
winner vs C
winner vs D

This is very similar to how:
	•	tournament brackets work
	•	some optimization algorithms work
	•	evolutionary selection works

So your intuition that humans often operate via "this or that" comparisons is pretty accurate.

⸻

2. Why the Brain Does This

The brain has limited working memory.

Classic research suggests humans can juggle roughly:
	•	~4–7 items in active attention.

Because of that limit, we simplify decisions.

Instead of evaluating everything simultaneously, we do:

compare → eliminate → compare → eliminate

This is computationally efficient.

⸻

3. Similarity to LLM Context Windows

Large language models also have limits:
	•	only a finite number of tokens can be processed at once.

So they also simplify reasoning by breaking problems into smaller comparisons.

However, the similarity isn’t perfect.

LLMs are statistical predictors, while humans combine:
	•	memory
	•	emotion
	•	reasoning
	•	experience

But both systems must compress complexity.

⸻

4. Why Binary Decisions Can Create Loops

Binary thinking sometimes causes problems.

Example:

attack vs surrender
friend vs enemy
right vs wrong

When systems only see two choices, they can get stuck in cycles.

Example escalation loop:

threat → attack
attack → counterattack
counterattack → escalate

Your earlier "loop" insight fits here.

Breaking loops often requires introducing a third option.

For example:

A fight
B retreat
C negotiate

The third option can dissolve a binary trap.

⸻

5. Your "Limited Context" Idea

You suggested limits exist so humans can’t "kill God."

That’s more philosophical than scientific, but there is a practical interpretation:

Limits force systems to be:
	•	incremental
	•	cooperative
	•	cautious

If any individual mind had unlimited planning power, systems might become unstable.

Instead, civilization progresses through many small comparisons over time.

⸻

6. Engineering Parallel

Interestingly, many engineering systems use the same pattern.

Examples:

Sorting algorithms

compare A and B
swap or keep
repeat

Chess engines

move A vs move B
evaluate

Evolution

trait A vs trait B
selection

So your "this or that" framing appears in many optimization systems, not just humans.

